Predictors of Acute Renal Failure Post-Heart Transplantation - A UNOS Analysis - BMIN503/EPID600 Final Project

Nosheen Reza, MD

Overview

There are no widely accepted or employed methods to predict the risk of early postoperative ARF requiring RRT after cardiac transplantation. The objective of this research is to derive and internally validate a clinical prediction model for postoperative ARF requiring RRT in HT recipients during the index transplantation hospitalization that can be deployed at the time a patient undergoes heart transplantation. The United Network for Organ Sharing (UNOS) database, a registry containing patient-level data on all solid organ transplants performed in the United States, will be used for model training and internal validation (80% training, 20% testing). My mentors for this project are Thomas Cappola, MD, ScM; Marylyn D. Ritchie, PhD; and Marina Serper, MD. With Dr. Cappola, I discussed clinically relevant predictors for my model. With Dr. Ritchie, I discussed the pros and cons of various prediction algorithms utilized in large clinical registries. With Dr. Serper, I discussed the bias/variance tradeoff. My final project GitHub repository is linked here:.

Introduction

Acute kidney injury (AKI) is a frequent post-operative complication after heart transplantation (HT) with a reported incidence as high as 70%. Approximately 10% of HT recipients with post-operative AKI develop acute renal failure (ARF) requiring renal replacement therapy (RRT) during the index transplantation admission. Post-HT ARF is associated with significant morbidity — including serious infection, post-HT chronic kidney disease, and prolonged hospitalization — and with postoperative mortality rates as high as 35-50%. In addition, post-cardiac surgery AKI is associated with higher total postoperative costs with patients requiring RRT generating up to 3-fold increase in costs compared with those with AKI not requiring RRT.

While several older single center retrospective studies have identified various risk factors for post-HT ARF, such as preoperative serum creatinine level, preoperative insulin-dependent diabetes, and cardiopulmonary bypass time, there remains an urgent need for a clinically relevant method to identify patients at risk for early post-HT renal failure requiring RRT, especially in the current era of high-risk bridging to HT with temporary mechanical circulatory support platforms.

In current practice, the pre-HT estimated glomerular filtration rate (eGFR) is the primary pre-HT clinical risk stratification tool for perioperative adverse renal events. Perioperative renoprotective strategies are limited to calcineurin inhibitor-sparing immunosuppression regimens and general avoidance of other potential nephrotoxins. Published single center inferential modeling studies of postoperative major adverse renal events have identified a range of predictor variables (e.g., age, serum albumin and creatinine levels, insulin-dependent diabetes, cardiopulmonary bypass time, cyclosporine use, intraoperative hypertension, intraoperative acidosis), although there are very few internal or external validation studies of these associations. There are no widely accepted or employed methods to predict the risk of early postoperative ARF requiring RRT after cardiac transplantation.

This project attempts to address an interdisciplinary issue that involves many medical disciplines, including cardiology, cardiothoracic surgery, critical care, anesthesia, and nephrology, and many types of clinicians, including physicians, advanced practice providers, nutritionists, pharmacists, and others. An important consideration of this modeling problem will be to create a model that is parsimonious and easily understood by clinicians given the nature of the input variables and the discrete outcome.

Data Source and Outcomes

The United Network for Organ Sharing (UNOS) database, a registry containing patient-level data on all solid organ transplants performed in the United States, will be used for model training and internal validation (80% training, 20% testing). Adult patients (>= 18 years old) who underwent heart transplantation between 2000 and 2020 will be included. Dual and triple organ recipients, retransplanted patients, and patients on pre-HT RRT will be excluded. Input variables will include pretransplant donor, recipient, and intraoperative characteristics provided by UNOS (i.e., demographics, comorbidities, hemodynamics, immunologic signatures). These are both continuous and discrete variables. Specifically, these data will be collected from the Transplant Candidate Registration (TCR), Transplant Recipient Registration (TRR), Deceased Donor Registration (DRR), and Donor Histocompatibility forms. Patients with >20% missing data will be excluded. Data from the Transplant Recipient Follow-up (TRF) form will not be used as these data are collected from a time horizon after the model’s intended use.

The primary outcome (training label) is the occurrence of new-onset postoperative ARF requiring RRT on the index HT hospital admission. This outcome is discrete with two classes (Dialysis, No Dialysis). This training label is expected to be an accurate marker of the real-world outcome of interest in practice given the standardized nature of data collection by the Organ Procurement and Transplantation Network (OPTN).

9. Exploratory data analyses - Part 2: Here, I limit the dataframe to only those columns with less than 5% missingness and then limit to complete cases. Then, I a priori select clinically relevant variables that I would like to model.

#table(analytic$pst_dial, useNA = "always") # 10.8% outcome occurrence in this cohort

# Limit dataset to variables with less than 5% missingness = 150 variables remaining
fivepct <- analytic %>% 
  purrr::discard(~sum(is.na(.x))/length(.x)* 100 >= 5)

# Then, limit to complete cases = 24918 observations remaining
fivepct_naomit <- na.omit(fivepct)
 
# A priori selection of clinically relevant variables - 31 variables, then collapsing some variables for modeling
t <- fivepct_naomit %>%
  select(c(pst_dial, diag, age, gender, ethcat, abo, bmi_tcr, ecmo_trr, iabp_trr, lvad_while_listed, rvad_while_listed, inotropes_trr, infect_iv_drug_trr, diab, creat_trr, hemo_sys_tcr, hemo_pa_dia_tcr, hemo_sys_trr, dayswait_chron, ventilator_trr, steroid, tbili, transfusions, age_don, gender_don, death_circum_don, bmi_don_calc, proc_ty_hr, ischtime, med_cond_trr)) %>%
  mutate(diag=fct_collapse(diag, 
                                Dilated = c("Dilated idiopathic", "Dilated adriamycin", "Dilated postpartum", "Dilated familial", "Dilated myocarditis", "Dilated alcoholic", "Dilated viral", "Dilated ischemic", "Dilated other"), 
                                Other = c("Other", "1602", "Heart Re-TX/Graft Issue"), 
                                Restrictive = c("Restrictive idiopathic", "Restrictive amyloidosis", "Restrictive endomyocardial fibrosis", "Restrictive sarcoidosis", "Restrictive radiation/chemotherapy", "Restrictive other"),
                                CAD = c("Coronary artery disease"), 
                                HCM = c("Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy"), 
                                VHD = c("Valvular heart disease"), 
                                CHD = c("Congenital heart disease"), 
                                ARVC = c("Arrhythmogenic right ventricular dysplasia/cardiomyopathy")
                                )) %>%
  mutate(abo=fct_collapse(abo,
                               A = c("A", "A1", "A1B", "A2", "A2B"),
                               B = c("B"),
                               AB = c("AB"),
                               O = c("O"))) %>%
  mutate(diab=fct_collapse(diab,
                           Yes = c("Type I", "Type II", "Type Other", "Type Unknown"),
                           No = c("No", "Diabetes Status Unknown"))) %>%
  mutate(death_circum_don=fct_collapse(death_circum_don, 
                                       Natural = c("Death from natural causes"),
                                       Nonnatural = c("MVA", "Suicide", "Homicide", "Non MVA", "None of the above")))

t$creat_trr[t$creat_trr > 8] <- 8 # Cutoff all creatinines higher than 8 to threshold of 8

t$bmi_tcr[t$bmi_tcr == 260207.6125] <- 26.0207

Prep for modeling: Here, I partition the data into 80% for training and 20% for testing.

#Split the data into train/test - 80/20 split

                                  list = FALSE, 
                                  times = 1)

Logistic regression using tidymodels: Logistic regression on 80% of dataset demonstrates that 18 significant predictors of the outcome with the diagnosis of congenital heart disease being the strongest predictor with an odds ratio of 3.77.

Combined ROC, PRC, sensitivity/specificity, and Calibration plots for logistic regression, ridge, lasso models

## Combined ROC plots
plot(performance(lrmodel_pred_obj, 'tpr','fpr'), main = 'ROC Curves', col='red')
plot(performance(cvridgemodel_pred_obj, 'tpr','fpr'), add=TRUE,col='blue')
plot(performance(cvlassomodel_pred_obj,'tpr','fpr'), add=TRUE,col='green')

## Combined PRC plots
plot(performance(lrmodel_pred_obj, 'prec','rec'), main = 'Precision Recall Curves', col='red')
plot(performance(cvridgemodel_pred_obj, 'prec','rec'),
     add=TRUE,col='blue')
plot(performance(cvlassomodel_pred_obj, 'prec','rec'),
     add=TRUE,col='green')

# Combined sensitivity specificity plots
plot(performance(lrmodel_pred_obj, 'sens','spec'), main = 'Sensitivity Specificity Curves', col='red')
plot(performance(cvridgemodel_pred_obj, 'sens','spec'),
     add=TRUE,col='blue')
plot(performance(cvlassomodel_pred_obj, 'sens','spec'),
     add=TRUE,col='green')

## Calibration plot
calib_df <- data.frame(outcome_f = as.factor(z),
                      outcome_n = z,
                      Logistic = lrmodel_test_preds,
                      Ridge = cvridgemodel_test_preds, 
                      Lasso = cvlassomodel_test_preds)
gmish::calib_plot(outcome_n ~ Logistic + Ridge + Lasso, dat = calib_df)

Conclusions: Cross-validated penalized regression models (i.e. Lasso and Ridge) do not perform any better than standard logistic regression modeling for this binary classifier problem. Overal AUCs were ~0.69, demonstrating that these variables are not excellent predictors of the outcome. From the calibration plot, it appears that for value of the predicted probability of < 50%, the models perform well. However, above that threshold, the model becomes inaccurate.
